data.title: Francisco Franco
data.meta_description: News about Francisco Franco, including commentary and archival articles published in The New York Times.
data.text:
Ángeles Flórez Peón, Spanish Civil War’s Last Militiawoman, Dies at 105

She was revered as an essential guardian of the country’s memory of war and repression long after the Franco dictatorship.

By Adam Nossiter

Guest Essay

Spain Is Doing Something Brave

A new amnesty law could be a remedy for democratic coexistence.

By Omar G. Encarnación

Far Right May Rise as Kingmaker in Spanish Election

A messier political landscape has lent leverage to the extremes, leaving a hard-right party with a chance to share power for the first time since Franco.

By Jason Horowitz

Guest Essay

Spain Is Going to Be Fine

Sunday’s election will determine the country’s political direction, not the fate of its democracy.

By Omar G. Encarnación

Theme Park’s Selective History Appeals to a New Spanish Nationalism

Puy du Fou España has drawn visitors with spectacular shows about Spanish history. But part of its success lies in what goes unsaid.

By Constant Méheut

Spanish Vote Threatens Efforts to Recover Franco’s Victims

Spain’s left-wing government has tried to accelerate exhumations of mass graves left from the dictatorship. If it wins Sunday’s election, the right may end that.

By Constant Méheut and Samuel Aranda
